# ZITADEL identity content — managed via the API, not git

All identity **content** — projects, roles, OIDC clients, external IdPs and
**above all who is in which group/role (user grants)** — is managed at runtime
through the ZITADEL API/console, never committed (invariant 6: GDPR + churn).
This runbook is how an agent does that work safely.

## The operator credential (per session, never stored)

The API credential is a **ZITADEL service-user PAT held by the operator** and
used **per session** — exported into the shell for one batch of work, then
discarded. It is an infrastructure credential (invariants 3 + 6):

- **never** committed (not plaintext, not sealed);
- **never** stored in the cluster — no service-account key, no PAT as a k8s
  secret.

Mint it in the console: Instance → Service Users → create a service user →
grant it the IAM-owner (or a narrower) manager role → generate a **Personal
Access Token**. Then for the session:

```bash
export ZITADEL_TOKEN="<service-user-PAT>"
export ZITADEL_HOST="https://id.{{ domain }}"
```

Helper for the calls below:

```bash
zreq() { curl -fsS -H "Authorization: Bearer $ZITADEL_TOKEN" \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' "$ZITADEL_HOST$@"; }
```

> **Anti-pattern (do not):** extracting the chart's `iam-admin` key and
> parking it on disk or as a k8s secret as a standing admin credential. Mint a
> scoped PAT, use it, discard it.

## Common operations

### Create a project / role

```bash
# project (in the community org)
zreq /management/v1/projects -d '{"name":"sports-club","projectRoleAssertion":true}'
# role on it
zreq /management/v1/projects/<project-id>/roles \
  -d '{"roleKey":"board","displayName":"board"}'
```

### Grant a user a role (membership) — never in git

```bash
zreq /management/v1/users/<user-id>/grants \
  -d '{"projectId":"<project-id>","roleKeys":["board"]}'
```

This is exactly the personal data that must stay out of version control.

### Create an OIDC client for an app

See `patterns/app-native-oidc/` for the field values; create it via
`/management/v1/projects/<project-id>/apps/oidc`, read back the client
secret **once**, and wire it into the app as a SealedSecret (app secrets are
the one thing that goes in git — invariant 3).

